That code also serves as a good example of how assumptions about a theoretical "optimizing compiler" can lead people into trouble.<p>Something like:<p><pre><code>  y[i] = y[i] + 0; 
</code></pre>
"Should" not take more time than:<p><pre><code>  y[i] = y[i] + 0.1; 
</code></pre>
because "any decent optimizing compiler obviously would NOP the entire statement out".<p>I seldom see it is the case though where compilers optimize things that coders assume it is obvious the compiler will optimize.

Consider this:<p><pre><code>  x += 0.0;
</code></pre>
If x = -0.0 (yes, zero has a sign) then adding 0.0 gives 0.0, so it <i>can</i> have an effect and optimizing it away is wrong and generally only allowed with -ffast-math.
